1: Abstract¶

Breast cancer is a serious global public health concern, and precise prediction of its occurrence is critical for early detection and effective treatment. This study investigates the use of Support Vector Machines (SVM) to detect breast cancer and compares its performance to other machine learning (ML) algorithms.

The dataset for this study includes several factors relating to patient characteristics, tumour attributes, and medical history. Preprocessing procedures are used to clean and normalise the data, making it suitable for use in predictive modelling. The dataset is then split into training and testing datasets.

Support Vector Machines, which are well-known for their ability to handle high-dimensional data, are being used to predict breast cancer. Cross-validation is used to fine-tune the hyperparameters of the SVM model to improve its performance.

2: Introduction¶

Breast cancer remains a pervasive and serious ailment, demanding advanced techniques for early detection and prognosis. Machine learning (ML) algorithms offer promising avenues for predictive modelling in medical domains, potentially improving diagnostic accuracy and patient outcomes. This study focuses on applying Support Vector Machines (SVM) to predict breast cancer, assessing its effectiveness and comparing it with other notable ML algorithms.

Accurate breast cancer prediction is crucial for timely interventions and tailored treatments, leading to better survival rates and reduced morbidity Siegel et al. (2020). ML algorithms, adept at handling complex datasets, hold promise for advancing medical diagnostics by capturing intricate patterns.

Support Vector Machines, known for handling high-dimensional data and non-linear relationships, provide a robust framework for predictive modelling as explained by Cortes & Vapnik (1995). By defining an optimal hyperplane to separate data points into distinct classes, SVMs discern patterns that conventional statistical methods may miss. However, the efficacy of SVM in breast cancer prediction requires exploration.

This report conducts a comparative study, evaluating SVM against ML algorithms like random forests, linear discriminant analysis (LDA), and logistic regression decision tree and gaussian naive bayes. Our goal is to determine the most accurate prediction algorithm for breast cancer by leveraging a comprehensive dataset containing patients medical history.

The study outcomes could enhance healthcare tools, enabling informed decision-making and improving patient care and treatment outcomes in breast cancer management.

3: Methodology¶

Data Processing and Visualization:

  • The dataset will be preprocessed to handle missing values, outliers, and ensure data quality.
  • Exploratory data analysis (EDA) techniques will be employed to gain insights into the distribution of features, identify patterns, and understand relationships between variables.

Feature Engineering and Dimensionality Reduction:

  • Relevant features will be selected or engineered from the dataset to improve model performance and interpretability.
  • Techniques such as dimensionality reduction, using Principal Component Analysis (PCA), will be applied to reduce the number of features while preserving important information.

Clustering Analysis:

  • Clustering algorithms, such as K-means clustering, will be applied to identify natural groupings or clusters within the dataset.
  • Clustering results will be visualized to explore inherent structures and potential subgroups within the data.

Building Support Vector Machine (SVM) Model:

  • A SVM model will be trained on the preprocessed dataset to predict breast cancer outcomes.
  • Hyperparameter tuning techniques, such as grid search, will be utilized to optimize the SVM model's performance.

Comparative Analysis:

  • The SVM model's performance will be evaluated and compared with other machine learning algorithms, including random forests, Linear Discriminant Analysis (LDA), and logistic regression, gaussianNB, decision tree.
  • Performance metrics such as accuracy, precision, recall, and F1-score will be calculated for each model to assess their predictive capabilities.

Conclusion:

  • The study outcomes will be summarized, highlighting the effectiveness of SVM and other algorithms in predicting breast cancer.
  • Insights gained from dimensionality reduction and clustering analysis will be discussed, along with implications for clinical practice and future research directions.

4: Analysis¶

4.1 Overview¶

Fine Needle Aspiration (FNA) is a minimally invasive procedure used for extracting cell samples from breast abnormalities. According to the blog post by Cancer Research UK (2023) This involves the insertion of a thin, hollow needle into the suspicious area, guided by ultrasound or mammography for precise targeting. Local anesthesia may be administered to minimize discomfort during the procedure, making FNA an efficient and well-tolerated method for obtaining diagnostic cell samples from breast tissues. which is then classified into:

  • 1 = Malignant (Cancerous): Indicates the presence of cancer.
  • 0 = Benign (Not Cancerous): Indicates the absence of cancer.

4.2 Objective¶

Because the labels used in the data are discrete, the prediction can be divided into two categories. In machine learning, this is a classification problem.

The goal is to categorise breast cancer as benign or malignantand to forecast the recurrence and non-recurrence of malignant instances after a given period. Weapplied machine learning classification algorithms to create a function capable of predicting the discrete class of fresh data.

4.3 Identify data sources and initial data processing¶

The dataset contains 569 samples of malignant and benign tumor cells. This report we would be using a modifed dataset provided by the course lecturer.

  • The first two columns in the dataset store the unique ID numbers of the samples and the corresponding diagnosis (M = malignant, B = benign), respectively.
  • The columns 3-32 contain 30 real-value features that have been computed from digitized images of the cell nuclei, which can be used to build a model to predict whether a tumor is benign or malignant.

In [11]:
from sklearn.impute import SimpleImputer

# Impute missing values for numerical columns with mean
numerical_imputer = SimpleImputer(strategy='mean')
df[numerical_features] = numerical_imputer.fit_transform(
    df[numerical_features])

# Impute missing values for categorical columns with most frequent value
categorical_imputer = SimpleImputer(strategy='most_frequent')
df[categorical_features] = categorical_imputer.fit_transform(
    df[categorical_features])

There are two approached used to examine the data:

  1. Descriptive statistics
  2. Visualization

Standardizing Features¶

4.6 Principal Component Analysis (PCA)¶

Upon reviewing the pair plot during Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA), several pairs of features display a noticeable separation of the data to a similar extent. Hence, it is reasonable to utilise PCA, a technique for reducing dimensionality. The objective is to use as many features as possible while retaining as much information as achievable when operating within a two-dimensional space, as elucidated by Gron (2019). Therefore, the decision is to utilise PCA.

In [43]:

4.7 K-means Clustring¶

In our analysis, Principal Component Analysis (PCA) was employed as a preliminary step to capture the essential variance within the dataset while reducing dimensionality. By examining the cumulative explained variance plot, a clear inflection point was observed at k=2 principal components. This observation suggests that a two-dimensional representation effectively retains significant information.

As a result, we have decided to utilize k=2 as the optimal number of clusters for our clustering analysis. This approach not only aids in computational efficiency but also aligns with the intrinsic structure of the data revealed through PCA.

In [47]:
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans

# Based on the elbow curve, choose the optimal number of clusters (k)
optimal_k = 2

# Apply k-means clustering
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=optimal_k, n_init=10, random_state=42)
clusters = kmeans.fit_predict(Xs)

# Get cluster centers
cluster_centers = kmeans.cluster_centers_

# Visualize the clusters
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))

# Scatter plot for data points

            cmap='cividis', label='Data Points', alpha=0.7)

# Scatter plot for cluster centers
plt.scatter(cluster_centers[:, 0], cluster_centers[:, 1],
            c='red', marker='X', s=200, label='Cluster Centers')

# Labels and title

4.8 Building a Predictive Model with Support Vector Machine (SVM)¶

We employ the Support Vector Machine (SVM) learning algorithm for building our predictive model. SVMs are well-known for classification tasks, proficiently managing non-linear data transformations. This capability allows the utilization of linear algorithms for model fitting, as noted in the work by Cortes and Vapnik (1995), referenced in Parmar (2020).

Kernelized SVMs exhibit robust performance on diverse datasets:

  1. SVMs accommodate intricate decision boundaries, even with limited features.

  2. They perform well on both low-dimensional and high-dimensional datasets, but scalability diminishes with an increasing number of samples.

    While effective with up to 10,000 samples, SVMs face challenges in runtime and memory usage with datasets exceeding 100,000 samples.

  3. SVMs necessitate meticulous data preprocessing and parameter tuning. Consequently, tree-based models like random forests or gradient boosting, requiring minimal preprocessing, are preferred in many scenarios.

  4. SVM models present challenges in interpretability; understanding specific predictions and explaining the model to non-experts can be intricate.

Key Parameters¶

Crucial parameters in kernel SVMs include:

  • Regularization parameter C,
  • Choice of kernel (linear, radial basis function (RBF), or polynomial),
  • Kernel-specific parameters.

The relationship between gamma and C impacts the complexity of the model, where higher values lead to a more intricate model. Therefore, it is recommended to adjust C and gamma simultaneously for optimal outcomes.

Classification with cross-validation¶

This process begins with a standard train/test split, followed by calculating cross-validation errors. The model with the lowest cross-validation error is selected for further evaluation.

In [51]:
# Split records into training and testing sets.

    Xs, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=2, stratify=y)

classifier = SVC(probability=True)

# Evaluate the accuracy of predictions on the remaining 30% of the test sample.
classifier_score = classifier.score(X_test, y_test)

    classifier_score))

In [54]:
# Print the scores.
print(scores)

# Calculate the average score and its uncertainty.
# - The mean score is multiplied by 100 to convert it into a percentage.
# - The standard deviation of the scores is divided by the square root of the number of samples to get the standard error of the mean.
# - The average score and its uncertainty are stored in the variable 'avg'.
avg = (100*np.mean(scores), 100*np.std(scores)/np.sqrt(scores.shape[0]))

# Print the average score and its uncertainty in a formatted string.
print(" The Average score and uncertainty: (%.2f +- %.3f)%%" % avg)

Model Accuracy: Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) curve¶

The ROC curve is a graphical representation of the performance of a binary classifier system as its discrimination threshold is varied. It plots two parameters: True Positive Rate (TPR) against the False Positive Rate (FPR). The area under the ROC curve, known as AUC, is a widely used measure of the performance of a classification model. A higher AUC indicates better discrimination ability in the model.

In [55]:

The classifier made a total of 174 predictions (there were 174 patients being tested for breast cancer). The classifier predicted "yes" 55 times out of 174 cases and "no" 116 times. In reality, 64 of the people in the sample have the condition and 107 do not.

  • For class "0" (Benign), the precision is 0.90, indicating that 90% of the samples predicted as Benign are actually Benign.
  • The recall for class "0" is 0.95, suggesting that 95% of the actual Benign samples are correctly identified.

  • The F1-score for class "0" is 0.93, which is the harmonic mean of precision and recall, providing a balanced measure of the model's performance for this class.

  • For class "1" (Malignant), the precision is 0.93, implying that 93% of the samples predicted as Malignant are indeed Malignant.

  • The recall for class "1" is 0.81, indicating that 81% of the actual Malignant samples are correctly classified.
  • The F1-score for class "1" is 0.87, representing a harmonic balance between precision and recall for Malignant class predictions.

Overall, the model achieves an accuracy of 91%, with an average precision, recall, and F1-score of 0.91. The macro-average and weighted-average scores are close to the overall accuracy, suggesting a balanced performance across both classes. However, it's important to note that there's a slightly lower recall for the Malignant class compared to Benign, indicating a potential area for improvement in correctly identifying Malignant cases.

Note: This difference in recall rates suggests that the model is better at identifying benign cases than malignant cases. Therefore, there may be room for improvement in the model's ability to correctly identify malignant cases. This could involve refining the features used for classification, adjusting model parameters, or employing more advanced modeling techniques to better capture the characteristics of malignant cases and improve their identification.

Significance of Classifier Optimization¶

Optimizing a classifier involves fine-tuning two crucial parameters within the SVM algorithm:

  • The regularization parameter ( C ), which determines the trade-off between maximizing the margin and minimizing the classification error.
  • The choice of kernel function, influencing the decision boundary's flexibility and the model's ability to capture complex patterns.

By default, SVM employs the Radial Basis Function (RBF) kernel, setting ( C ) to 1.0. However, exploring alternative kernel types and varying ( C ) values can lead to improved model performance. To achieve this, we employ a grid search approach coupled with 10-fold cross-validation on a standardized version of the training dataset. This enables us to assess the model's performance across different parameter configurations, ranging from simpler to more complex kernels and bias levels.

In Python's scikit-learn library, two primary methods facilitate algorithm parameter tuning:

  • Grid Search Parameter Tuning: Exhaustively searches through a specified parameter grid to find the optimal combination.
  • Random Search Parameter Tuning: Randomly samples from the parameter space, offering computational efficiency while still providing effective parameter optimization.

In [69]:
from sklearn.exceptions import ConvergenceWarning
import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings("ignore", category=ConvergenceWarning)

# Spot-Check Algorithms
models = []

# Append different classification algorithms along with their abbreviations
models.append(('LR', LogisticRegression()))  # Logistic Regression
# Linear Discriminant Analysis
models.append(('LDA', LinearDiscriminantAnalysis()))
# Classification and Regression Trees
models.append(('CART', DecisionTreeClassifier()))
models.append(('NB', GaussianNB()))  # Gaussian Naive Bayes
models.append(('SVM', SVC()))  # Support Vector Machine
models.append(('RF', RandomForestClassifier()))  # Random Forest


# Test options and evaluation metric
num_folds = 10  # Number of folds for cross-validation
num_instances = len(X_train)  # Number of instances in the training data
seed = 7  # Seed for random number generator for reproducibility
scoring = 'accuracy'  # Evaluation metric

# Initialize lists to store results
results = []  # Stores cross-validation results
names = []  # Stores names of classifiers

# Iterate over each classifier
for name, model in models:
    # Define k-fold cross-validation
    kfold = KFold(n_splits=num_folds, random_state=seed, shuffle=True)

    # Perform cross-validation and store results
    cv_results = cross_val_score(
        model, X_train, y_train, cv=kfold, scoring=scoring)
    results.append(cv_results)
    names.append(name)

    # Print mean and standard deviation of cross-validation results
    msg = "%s: %f (%f)" % (name, cv_results.mean(), cv_results.std())
    print(msg)

# Print a descriptive message indicating the completion of cross-validation
print('\n 10-Fold cross-validation accuracy score for the training data for six classifiers')

              {'clf__C': param_range, 'clf__gamma': param_range,
               'clf__kernel': ['rbf']}]
gs_svm = GridSearchCV(estimator=pipe_svc,
                      param_grid=param_grid,
                      scoring='accuracy',
                      cv=10,
                      n_jobs=1)

Summary¶

The parameter optimization results for various machine learning algorithms on the test dataset are as follows:

Support Vector Machine (SVM) achieved an accuracy of 95.91%. The confusion matrix indicates that it correctly classified 113 instances of class B and 51 instances of class M, with only 3 false positives and 4 false negatives. The precision, recall, and F1-score for both classes are high, indicating robust performance.

Logistic Regression attained an accuracy of 95.32%. It correctly classified 112 instances of class B and 51 instances of class M, with 4 false positives and 4 false negatives. Similar to SVM, the precision, recall, and F1-score for both classes are commendable.

Linear Discriminant Analysis (LDA) also achieved an accuracy of 95.32%. It correctly classified 116 instances of class B and 47 instances of class M, with no false positives but 8 false negatives. While the precision for class M is perfect, the recall is slightly lower, leading to a lower F1-score for class M compared to class B.

Random Forest yielded the highest accuracy of 96.49%. It correctly classified 112 instances of class B and 53 instances of class M, with 4 false positives and 2 false negatives. The precision, recall, and F1-score for both classes are high, indicating strong performance similar to SVM.

In conclusion, after parameter optimization, all algorithms demonstrated high accuracy and generally performed well in classifying instances of class B and class M. Random Forest slightly outperformed the other algorithms in terms of accuracy, but all models achieved satisfactory results.

5: Conclusion¶

The study explores the application of machine learning algorithms, particularly Support Vector Machines (SVM), in predicting breast cancer outcomes. It emphasizes the importance of accurate prediction for early detection, tailored treatment plans, and improved patient outcomes. The study incorporates dimensionality reduction and clustering techniques to enhance model performance and interpretability. It compares SVM with other algorithms like random forests, Linear Discriminant Analysis (LDA), and logistic regression to determine the most effective predictive model. The findings have significant implications for clinical practice, including improved diagnostic accuracy, tailored treatment plans, and early detection. Future research directions include integrating biomarker data, longitudinal data analysis, external validation, and clinical implementation of predictive models. These efforts aim to advance breast cancer prediction and contribute to better patient outcomes and quality of care.
